    <p class="draft-meta">
      <em>What two and a half centuries of American school trust lands teach
      the architects of AI-era institutions.</em>
      <br />
      <small>By Dave Sullivan, founder, <a href="/">America's School Trust Library</a>. Skeleton v1, drafted 2026-05-14. Target final length 4,000–6,000 words.</small>
    </p>

    <h2>Opening</h2>

    <p>
      In May of 1785, the Confederation Congress slid a single sentence
      into a long surveying ordinance. Section sixteen of every
      six-mile-square township in the new western country, the sentence
      said, would be reserved for the maintenance of public schools. It
      is, as far as anyone has been able to find, the longest-running
      multi-generational fiduciary experiment ever attempted by a
      national government. It has been running, continuously, for two
      hundred and forty years. The data from it is in. And the
      architects of a new round of forever-trusts — AI Targeting
      Authorities, perpetual climate trusts, sovereign wealth funds
      chartered for the unborn, longevity escrows, data trusts, compute
      reserves — are, in the year this essay is being written, drafting
      their charters without that data on their desks. This essay is an
      attempt to put it there.
    </p>

    <p>
      The framers built well. The trust form they reached for had been
      hardening in English equity courts since 1601, and the language
      they used — <em>for no other use, intent or purpose whatever</em>,
      in the 1803 Ohio implementing act; <em>deemed a breach of trust</em>,
      in the 1910 New Mexico–Arizona Enabling Act — is among the
      strongest perpetual-purpose language any common-law tradition has
      produced. The architecture worked where it was installed. Utah's
      contemporary school trust holds approximately $3.2 billion; New
      Mexico's, approximately $30 billion; Texas's, $56–67 billion. The
      1910 New Mexico–Arizona Enabling Act produced the high-water mark
      of federal trust language, expressly authorizing the federal
      Attorney General to enforce.
    </p>

    <p>
      The architecture also failed where it failed. California's 1853
      grant omitted the "in trust" clause; the state has retained
      roughly 8–10 percent of its original 5.5-million-acre school
      grant. Oregon's Common School Fund, at the bottom of its
      trajectory in 1907, was at one-fifth of what the framers' design
      would have produced — by the state's own governor's accounting.
      Mississippi sold its sixteenth sections for a dollar an acre in
      the 1820s and there were no marches in the streets. Utah's
      legislature withdrew $37.5 million from the permanent fund in a
      single fiscal year in 1983, dropping the corpus from $53.5
      million to $18.6 million in twelve months. Nebraska's governor,
      twenty-two days before this essay's first draft, signed a bill
      sweeping $40 million from a school-trust mechanism into a
      discretionary K-12 spending fund. The aggregate forgone value
      across the public-land states is somewhere between $80 billion
      and $120 billion in 2026 dollars.
    </p>

    <p>
      The case for sharing this evidence with the AI-governance
      community is not that they have failed. It is that we already
      have. The cognitive bias, the bureaucratic self-preservation, the
      politically silent beneficiary — these are not pathologies of
      nineteenth-century state government. They are the standard
      failure pattern of any aspirational structure with
      intergenerational beneficiaries, and the same pattern is loaded
      into every charter being drafted in 2026.
    </p>

    <p>
      What follows is what the school-trust record teaches, anchor by
      anchor, to the people drafting those charters now.
    </p>

    <h2>The eight anchors</h2>

    <h3>Anchor 1 — Codified fiduciary duties</h3>

    <p>
      The empirical floor here is the gap between Arizona and New
      Mexico. Same federal text, on the same day — the New Mexico–Arizona
      Enabling Act of June 20, 1910, with its express "in trust"
      language and its "deemed a breach of trust" provision for
      non-conforming dispositions. By 2026, New Mexico's permanent fund
      holds approximately $30 billion. Arizona's holds approximately $8
      billion. Same words, different outcomes by a factor of nearly
      four. California, by contrast, received in its 1853 federal grant
      only the phrase "for the purposes of public schools," with no "in
      trust" language at all; the California Supreme Court read the
      omission as decisive in <em>Sherman v. Buick</em> (1876), and the
      state has retained one-tenth of its original grant. The duty must
      be on the page, in operationally specific terms, before any of
      the rest of the architecture can do its work. The AI translation:
      every founding charter for an AI Targeting Authority, a climate
      trust, a data trust, a compute reserve must declare, in terms
      equivalent to the 1910 breach-of-trust language, that any
      diversion of the structure's resources from beneficiary-mission
      purposes is a breach of trust, voidable in court, recoverable by
      independent enforcement. The Ohio 1803 <em>for no other use,
      intent or purpose whatever</em> clause is the period's strongest
      closure of the political-discretion exception, and the AI-era
      charter needs its operational equivalent: <em>no compute hour,
      capital dollar, or attention-directing grant disbursed by the
      Authority shall be applied to any purpose other than the
      long-term welfare of the beneficiary class identified in this
      charter</em>. Anything weaker than that and the doctrinal floor
      is missing — and the school-trust record says that the
      architecture without that doctrinal floor erodes to one-tenth of
      its design within a century and a half.
    </p>

    <h3>Anchor 2 — Asset restoration</h3>

    <p>
      Aspirational structures lose ground in increments — a small
      diversion here, a transfer to a different fund there, a sale
      below appraised value across a budget cycle no one is watching.
      The 1889 Omnibus Enabling Act, which admitted North Dakota, South
      Dakota, Montana, and Washington, introduced the "null and void"
      clause precisely for this reason: any disposition of school-trust
      lands outside the granted purposes was nullified by operation of
      federal text, which gave the trust a doctrinal hook to convert
      breach into recovery. Utah's 1998 Schools and Lands Exchange Act
      is the cleanest contemporary instance of recovery in operation:
      377,000 trust acres trapped within the 1996 Grand
      Staircase–Escalante National Monument were exchanged out for $50
      million in cash and equivalent federal lands, converting
      political loss into trust gain. The recovery worked because the
      underlying breach was nullifiable on the founding text. Where the
      founding text supplies no nullification hook — California — the
      recovery does not happen. The AI translation: every grant cycle's
      disbursements should be auditable against the founding text; any
      disbursement found to have violated the beneficiary-mission
      purpose should be nullified by operation of charter, with the
      resources recoverable to the corpus through independent
      enforcement. Political reversal is contingent. Nullification by
      operation of charter is structural. The charter must build the
      recovery hook into its founding language, because the
      architecture cannot rely on the political conditions of any later
      decade being favorable to the restoration.
    </p>

    <h3>Anchor 3 — Individual and institutional accountability</h3>

    <p>
      The school-trust record's hardest lesson on accountability is
      double. Boards have a way of dissolving responsibility — a vote
      is taken, the consequences are diffuse, individual trustees
      later report that they acted as the board acted. The trust-law
      tradition, older than the modern administrative board, holds
      that a trustee who participates in a breach is personally liable
      for the breach, in the same sense a charitable-trust trustee at
      common law is liable. Modern public-trust statutes have, almost
      without exception, blurred that rule. Oregon's State Land Board,
      between 1990 and 2017, made the operational decisions that
      converted a century of stewardship into a documented pattern of
      breach, but the breach is not legible at the level of any
      individual trustee's vote; it is legible only at the level of
      the institution. The state itself owes restitution, regardless
      of which trustee's name is on which 1997 minute. Calling
      individual trustees to account is a forensic question. Calling
      the state to account is a fiduciary one — that is Margaret
      Bird's framing, and it is what closes the institutional escape
      hatch that diffused responsibility otherwise opens. The AI
      translation: every officer, board member, and trustee of the new
      aspirational structure is personally liable, by operation of
      charter, for any act treating the structure's assets as
      non-structure assets. The structure itself, as an entity, is
      liable for the institutional drift the individual votes ratify.
      The charter must refuse both escape routes simultaneously,
      because the school-trust record shows that an architecture that
      holds only one is the architecture that diffused responsibility
      eventually finds its way around.
    </p>

    <h3>Anchor 4 — Direct distribution</h3>

    <p>
      The Utah School LAND Trust Program, established by the Utah
      Legislature in 1999, distributes a portion of the trust's
      earnings on a per-pupil basis directly to individual public
      schools — visible to teachers, parents, and principals at the
      building level, governed by a School Community Council at each
      school that by statute must have a parent majority and that
      adopts an annual academic plan. The visibility produces an
      enforcement constituency at scale: when a Utah governor moves to
      raid the fund, the political response comes not from a single
      advocacy office but from every school in the state whose annual
      disbursement is on the table. The mechanism converts
      beneficiaries who cannot vote — the children — into surrogate
      beneficiaries who can — their parents, their teachers, and the
      local civic infrastructure that already exists around every
      classroom. The contrast that proves the point is the wallet
      metaphor: in states without direct distribution, the schools are
      not beneficiaries in any operational sense; they are
      <em>payees</em>. The state hands the schools their own money
      back from the general fund and calls the transaction a
      distribution. That is what handing a wallet to its rightful
      owner, after first removing what was inside the wallet, looks
      like. It is not what a fiduciary distribution looks like. The AI
      translation, which is harder to specify and more important to
      get right: the beneficiary class for an AI Targeting Authority —
      future humans — does not receive grants in any direct sense.
      What can be made visible is the grant-by-grant decision record
      itself. Every grant named and dated; every decision rule
      traceable; every dissent recorded; every grant's downstream
      consequences audited at intervals the charter specifies. Without
      that visibility, no constituency forms; without a constituency,
      no architecture defends itself.
    </p>

    <h3>Anchor 5 — Independent beneficiary advocacy</h3>

    <p>
      Utah's Land Trusts Protection and Advocacy Office, codified at
      Title 53D Chapter 2 in 2018, is statutorily separate from the
      management agency. It has its own director, its own budget, its
      own mandate to argue against state uses of trust assets that
      conflict with trust purposes. Section 53D-2-201 directs the
      office to represent beneficiary interests across land
      management, fund investment, and distributions. The office's job
      description begins and ends with the welfare of the beneficiary.
      California, Oregon, and most other states do not have an
      equivalent office; the predicted consequence — drift uncontested,
      year by year, until litigation forces a public reckoning — is
      the consequence the school-trust record displays in those
      states. The Project Bold case in Utah (1982–1984), where a
      sophisticated actor inside the system attempted to convert the
      trust by burying the operative language on page 124 of a
      200-page proposal, is the diagnostic illustration: the remedy is
      not "more attention to drift." The remedy is a beneficiary
      advocate who reads page 124. The AI translation: every new
      aspirational structure needs an Office of the Future-Beneficiary
      Advocate, statutorily separate from management, with a
      fixed-term directorship insulated from removal except for cause,
      with its own appropriation, with an annual report published
      independently of the structure's own report. The 2055 humans
      whose welfare is in the Authority's portfolio cannot show up in
      2030 to argue their case. Someone has to show up for them, and
      that someone has to draw a paycheck from a different
      appropriation than the management entity's. Without that
      structural separation, the advocacy collapses back into another
      function of management, and the future-beneficiary class loses
      its only voice in the room.
    </p>

    <h3>Anchor 6 — Specialized legal defense</h3>

    <p>
      State Attorneys General are political officers whose duties run,
      in most states, to multiple state clients with conflicting
      interests. When the trust's interests conflict with the state's
      general-fund interests — and they always do, eventually — the
      Attorney General is structurally compromised. The 1910 New
      Mexico–Arizona Enabling Act § 10 got this right, expressly
      authorizing enforcement by the Attorney General of the United
      States <em>as well as</em> by the state and by individual
      citizens. Plural enforcement built into the federal text.
      Oregon's 2026 litigation history is the contemporary cautionary
      case: the Oregon Attorney General's office, defending the
      state's position in <em>Advocates for School Trust Lands v.
      State of Oregon</em>, has had to argue against the same
      trust-character framing the same office's own opinions had
      endorsed in 1983, 1992, and 2003. A trust whose own counsel can
      swap interpretations across two decades is a trust whose legal
      sword is structurally compromised. The AI translation: when the
      structure's interests conflict with the entities that fund it,
      host its compute, or supply its political legitimacy — and they
      will, on the historical evidence, conflict early and often — the
      structure must have its own counsel, selected by the Office of
      the Future-Beneficiary Advocate, paid by the structure's own
      resources, accountable solely to the trust. Plural enforcement
      should be present at the founding: enforcement by the
      structure's own counsel, by independent third-party enforcers,
      <em>and</em> by individual citizens with statutory standing to
      sue on behalf of the future-beneficiary class. The redundancy is
      the design feature.
    </p>

    <h3>Anchor 7 — Mandatory fiduciary education</h3>

    <p>
      State Land Boards in most public-land states are composed of
      elected officials — typically the governor, secretary of state,
      and state treasurer — whose primary professional formation is
      political rather than fiduciary. Oregon wrote this directly into
      Article VIII, Section 5 of its 1857 Constitution. Most such
      trustees have no specific training in trust law, the rule of
      undivided loyalty, the prudent-investor standard, or the
      operational meaning of the sole-interest rule. The Cardozo
      standard — the <em>punctilio of an honor the most sensitive</em>,
      from <em>Meinhard v. Salmon</em> (1928) — is the highest
      standard fiduciary law knows, and it is also the standard most
      public trustees have never been taught. The defense the
      school-trust record names is annual training, by statute: a
      structured curriculum on the fiduciary duties of public
      trustees, taught by independent practitioners (not by the
      agencies the trustees oversee), with documented completion as a
      condition of remaining in office. The training is the cognitive
      recalibration the political mind otherwise misses. The AI
      translation: the governance committee of an AI Targeting
      Authority will be composed predominantly of officials whose
      primary professional formation is technical or political — AI
      researchers, philanthropic executives, government appointees.
      Annual training on the fiduciary duties of trust officers —
      taught by independent practitioners, not by the Authority's own
      legal staff — should be a charter-mandated condition of
      remaining in office. The training's content should include the
      school-trust record itself, treated as a worked case study of
      what fiduciary failure across two centuries actually looks like.
      The trustee disposition is not the natural disposition of the
      technologist or the elected official; the difference has to be
      taught and re-taught at intervals that match the pace at which
      it is forgotten.
    </p>

    <h3>Anchor 8 — The watchful crew (the standing constituency)</h3>

    <p>
      The seven anchors above are the formal architecture. Each has at
      least one operational instance somewhere in the public-land
      states. But anchors do not set themselves. Anchors do not check
      themselves. An anchor that no one inspects is, at the next
      storm, indistinguishable from no anchor at all. The eighth
      anchor is the watchful crew — the standing constituency, across
      generational time, that holds the seven enforceable. The
      school-trust record is unambiguous on this point: Oregon's
      pre-1990 architecture was, for its century, among the strongest
      in the country, and the drift came anyway because the cohort of
      state foresters, school administrators, and legislative-culture
      insiders who had insisted on the architecture in operational
      practice dissipated faster than the architecture could
      compensate for. Utah's contemporary record, by contrast, is the
      joint product of strong architecture <em>and</em> an active
      community of trustees, advocates, parents, teachers,
      journalists, and legislators who treat the architecture as
      binding. The framers of 1785 had no instrument with which to
      build a multi-generational civic-attention infrastructure; the
      cognitive technology of 1785 — quill, paper, statute book, mail
      moving by horse, fragile human memory in heads spread across a
      continent without telegraph or rail — could not hold
      institutional context across the generations the trust was
      meant to bind. The cognitive technology of 2026 can. AI-augmented
      research has dropped the per-citizen cost of competence on a
      complex multi-generational asset by at least an order of
      magnitude in the past four years. A retired tree farmer in Coos
      County can now ask, in a single afternoon, what would have taken
      a state archivist in 1986 a month: the trust's current acreage,
      historical revenue per acre, comparable states' classroom
      disbursements, the figures restated in 2026 dollars. The AI
      translation is the most important single recommendation in this
      essay: every new aspirational structure should name its
      watchful-crew institution at the founding — a public-substrate
      library on the model of America's School Trust Library at
      schooltrusts.net, capable of holding the structure's
      institutional memory across generational cycles, funded from
      the structure's corpus on a statutorily protected appropriation,
      insulated from removal except for cause. The seven anchors are
      necessary. The eighth is what makes the seven enforceable across
      the time horizons that aspirational structures actually face.
      The architects who build only the seven will discover, in the
      2080s, that the founding text alone is not enforcing itself. The
      school-trust record is unambiguous on this point.
    </p>

    <h2>Closing — why now</h2>

    <p>
      The first-mover argument is the simple one. The AI-era
      institutions being designed in 2026 cannot draw on
      multi-generational empirical evidence from anywhere else in
      human history. The European pension funds are post-war; the
      sovereign wealth funds are post-1970; the modern philanthropic
      foundations are post-1900. None of them has the running time the
      school trust has. None of them has been pressure-tested across
      the kinds of political ruptures the public-land states have run
      their school trusts through — Civil War, Reconstruction, two
      world wars, the Great Depression, multiple state-level
      constitutional revisions, and four decades of accelerating
      fiscal politics. The school trust is the only institution
      available, in any common-law jurisdiction, that has been
      operated continuously for long enough to produce statistically
      meaningful data on how aspirational structures behave under
      intergenerational pressure.
    </p>

    <p>
      The data is in. The pathology is structural — three forces
      (hyperbolic discounting, eusocial drift, the politically silent
      beneficiary) compound into two failure modes (gradual drift and
      directed seizure), and the defenses against both are knowable,
      specifiable, and installable. The window for installation is
      now, while the charters are still being drafted. Once the
      structures harden into their operating forms — and the
      school-trust evidence suggests this happens within the first
      decade of operation, when administrative routines settle and
      constituencies form around whatever the structure permits — the
      architecture is harder to amend by an order of magnitude. Oregon
      has been spending reform capital on the Common School Fund for
      the better part of fifty years without restoring the corpus to
      its design. The architects who install the seven anchors and
      name the watchful-crew institution at founding will avoid that
      fifty-year retrofit cost. The architects who do not will
      discover, fifty years on, that the structure they built has been
      converted into something else by people who at every step had
      defensible reasons.
    </p>

    <p>
      The Library at schooltrusts.net hosts the <em>Schools of the
      Republic</em> encyclopedia, the <em>Eighth Anchor</em> white
      paper from which this essay is drawn, the per-state evidentiary
      record, the weekly Newsroom that surveys the fifty states, and
      the Map Room that tracks state-by-state transparency posture. It
      is the first public-facing instance of an institutional
      infrastructure that does for a multi-generational fiduciary
      structure what the timber-frame revival of the 1970s did for a
      civic craft that had nearly disappeared from working memory:
      archaeological recovery of the technique, plain-language books
      that let others replicate, institutional infrastructure,
      workshops and community accumulation that compound the technique
      faster than any one practitioner could on her own. The Library
      is the existence proof that the watchful-crew function is
      buildable, at workable cost, in 2026 rather than in 2226.
    </p>

    <p>
      The invitation to the AI-governance community is concrete. Read
      the eight-essay white paper. Take what transfers. Build the
      watchful-crew institution at the founding of every new
      aspirational structure your work touches. The framers of 1785
      did not have the cognitive technology to engineer the eighth
      anchor at their founding; the framers of 2026 do. The choice is
      yours. The school-trust record will be on the desk when you are
      ready to use it.
    </p>

    <p>
      Conversations welcome — at schooltrusts.net, by direct email, or
      at any of the venues where the Library's work is being presented
      over the next eighteen months. The next round of aspirational
      structures will be defined by whether their architects took this
      lesson on board or did not. The school trust has carried the
      case as far as one institution can. The next institutions will
      carry it farther — or they will not. That choice is what this
      essay exists to put on the page.
    </p>

    <h2>Open questions</h2>

    <p>
      <em>The skeleton is visibly in working form. Several decisions
      remain open before the essay graduates to a finished piece;
      they are listed here in the spirit of the Writing Room — the
      working state is not hidden.</em>
    </p>

    <ul>
      <li>
        <strong>Title choice.</strong> The default working title is
        "The Only Forever-Trust We Have Data On…" An alternative
        framing — "The Eighth Anchor: A Working Manual from a 240-Year
        Natural Experiment" — borrows the Library's central frame and
        may land better with audiences already familiar with the
        Sacred Compact.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Aggregate-forgone-value figure.</strong> The "$80–$120
        billion in 2026 dollars" figure in the opening is implied by
        Chamberlain's 1907 "five or six times as large" formulation
        generalized across the public-land states. It is not a number
        defensible with a single citation in the way the Utah 1983
        $37.5 million withdrawal is defensible. Retain, soften
        ("between roughly $75 billion and $150 billion, on plausible
        state-by-state reconstructions"), or rely on per-state numbers
        alone?
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Margaret Bird attribution.</strong> The "forever gift
        to forever schools for a forever democracy" framing is hers
        and is canonical to the Library. The wallet metaphor (anchor
        4) and the "calling the state to account" framing (anchor 3)
        are also hers; the draft quotes them on implicit attribution
        for prose flow. Per the May 12 doctrine the Library's public
        surfaces carry Sullivan's byline alone — should Margaret be
        named in a single closing sentence ("The phrase is Margaret
        Bird's") or kept on implicit attribution?
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Diamandis/Wissner-Gross naming.</strong> The
        <em>Solve Everything</em> AI Targeting Authority proposal is
        the immediate referent. Lead with that specific proposal
        (makes the essay's relevance immediate to anyone who has read
        the book) or stay more general (broader addressable
        readership, loses the hook)?
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Length.</strong> The skeleton runs ~2,350 words;
        expanded to draft it lands at 4,800–5,200, within the
        4,000–6,000 target but at the long end. Draft toward 5,000 or
        toward 4,200?
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Closing CTA.</strong> The closing invites conversation
        generically. Carry a specific contact channel
        (<a href="mailto:drdavesullivan@gmail.com">drdavesullivan@gmail.com</a>),
        the Library's contact form, or both? And whether to include a
        sentence about the Margaret-endorsement-pending status of the
        Library — or keep that internal-only?
      </li>
    </ul>
